<h1>Introduction to IoT & Device Communication</h1>

<h2>What is IoT?</h2>

<p>
Internet of Things (IoT) is a technology where physical devices
are connected to the internet to collect, exchange and process data.
IoT devices use sensors, networks and software to perform smart actions.
</p>


<h2>IoT Architecture</h2>

<div class="box">

<h3>1. Devices / Sensors</h3>
<p>
Sensors collect data from the environment like temperature,
humidity, motion and pressure.
</p>

<h3>2. Network</h3>
<p>
The network transfers sensor data using WiFi, Bluetooth,
or other communication technologies.
</p>


<h3>3. Cloud</h3>
<p>
Cloud stores and processes IoT data and provides services
for users.
</p>


<h3>4. User Application</h3>
<p>
Users monitor and control IoT systems through applications.
</p>

</div>


<h2>Data Flow in IoT System</h2>

<p>

Sensor → Network → Cloud → Application → User

</p>


<h2>Real World IoT Applications</h2>

<ul>

<li>Smart Home Automation</li>

<li>Smart Agriculture</li>

<li>Health Monitoring System</li>

<li>Smart Cities</li>

</ul>


<h2>Device Communication</h2>

<p>
IoT devices communicate with each other by sending data
through wireless networks. Sensors collect information,
send it to the cloud, and the system performs required actions.
</p>


